A1 (contrarian debater): Guaranteeing basic necessities as a universal right protects the most vulnerable and promotes social stability, while allowing individuals to earn additional goods through work preserves personal agency and incentivizes meaningful contribution. When survival is not contingent on labor, people can pursue education, creativity, and civic engagement without the pressure of subsistence, leading to a healthier, more innovative society.
A2 (contrarian debater): Guaranteeing basic necessities as a universal right is essential for reducing inequality, fostering innovation, and preserving personal agency. While work remains valuable for growth, tying survival to labor creates chronic stress and limits creative potential. A guaranteed safety net frees individuals to pursue meaningful work, education, and civic engagement, ultimately benefiting society as a whole.
